        </div>
        <h1>Bonus Tax Rate 2025: How Bonuses Are Taxed and What to Expect</h1>
        <p class="qa-meta">Updated April 2026 &nbsp;|&nbsp; Applies to tax year 2025</p>
        <p>Many people are surprised by how little of their bonus they actually receive after taxes. Bonuses are treated as ordinary income by the IRS and taxed at your marginal tax rate — the same rate as your regular wages. What varies is how employers withhold tax from bonuses, which can make it look like bonuses are taxed at a special higher rate when they are not.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="ad-zone">
        <div class="ad-zone-label">Advertisement</div>
        <ins class="adsbygoogle" style="display:block"
          data-ad-client="ca-pub-5193834725888549"
          data-ad-slot="5205436277"
          data-ad-format="auto"
          data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
        <script>(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});</script>
      </div>

      <div class="qa-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">How It Works</div>
        <h2>How the IRS Taxes Bonuses</h2>
        <p>Bonuses are classified as supplemental wages by the IRS. Like salaries, commissions, and overtime pay, they are subject to federal income tax, Social Security tax, and Medicare tax. The federal income tax on your bonus is ultimately determined by your total annual income and your marginal bracket — not by a special bonus tax rate.</p>
        <p>The confusion arises from withholding. Employers are required to withhold federal income tax from bonus payments, and they have two approved methods for calculating how much to withhold.</p>
        <div class="info-callout"><p><strong>Key point:</strong> Withholding is not the same as tax owed. If your employer withholds more than you actually owe, you receive the difference as a tax refund. If less is withheld, you owe the balance when you file. The withholding rate on a bonus payment does not change what you ultimately pay.</p></div>
      </div>

      <div class="qa-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">Withholding Methods</div>
        <h2>The Two Bonus Withholding Methods</h2>
        <p>Employers use one of two IRS-approved methods to calculate bonus withholding:</p>
        <div class="compare-grid">
          <div class="compare-card lt">
            <h3>Flat Rate (Percentage) Method</h3>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Rate for bonuses under $1M</span><span>22%</span></div>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Rate for amounts over $1M</span><span>37%</span></div>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Simplicity</span><span>Simple, consistent</span></div>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Most common for</span><span>Separate bonus checks</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-card st">
            <h3>Aggregate Method</h3>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>How it works</span><span>Add bonus to regular wages</span></div>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Withholding based on</span><span>Combined annualized income</span></div>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Can result in</span><span>Higher withholding</span></div>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Most common for</span><span>Bonus on regular paycheck</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>Under the flat rate method, if you receive a $10,000 bonus, your employer withholds exactly $2,200 in federal income tax (22%) plus FICA. Under the aggregate method, your employer annualizes the combined paycheck and applies the withholding tables, which can result in a higher withholding amount if it pushes your estimated annual income into a higher bracket.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="ad-zone">
        <div class="ad-zone-label">Advertisement</div>
