        <script>(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({{}});</script>
      </div>

      <div class="qa-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">Real Tax Rate</div>
        <h2>Your Actual Tax Rate on the Bonus</h2>
        <p>Your true federal income tax on a bonus is determined by your marginal bracket — the same rate that applies to the last dollar of your regular income. If you are a single filer with $70,000 in taxable income before the bonus, the 22% bracket applies to income from $48,475 to $103,350, so a bonus that keeps you within that range is taxed at 22%.</p>
        <div class="example-calc">
          <h3>Example: Single filer, $70,000 salary + $10,000 bonus</h3>
          <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Total taxable income</span><span class="value">$80,000</span></div>
          <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Marginal rate on bonus</span><span class="value">22%</span></div>
          <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Federal income tax on $10,000 bonus</span><span class="value">~$2,200</span></div>
          <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Social Security (6.2%)</span><span class="value">$620</span></div>
          <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Medicare (1.45%)</span><span class="value">$145</span></div>
          <div class="example-row total"><span class="label">Estimated net bonus received</span><span class="value">~$7,035</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="qa-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">Tax Strategy</div>
        <h2>How to Reduce Taxes on Your Bonus</h2>
        <p>There is no way to avoid paying income tax on a bonus — it is ordinary income. But there are legitimate strategies to minimize the tax impact.</p>
        <p><strong>Maximize 401(k) contributions.</strong> If you have not yet hit the $23,500 limit, increase your deferral rate before your bonus is paid. Pre-tax 401(k) contributions reduce your taxable income dollar for dollar, directly reducing the bracket exposure of your bonus.</p>
        <p><strong>Contribute to an HSA.</strong> If you are enrolled in an HDHP, an HSA contribution reduces your AGI by up to $4,300 (self-only) or $8,550 (family) and can offset some of the bonus income.</p>
        <p><strong>Time other deductions.</strong> If you itemize, making a large charitable contribution or paying a deductible expense in the same year as a big bonus can help offset the income.</p>
        <div class="tip-callout"><p><strong>Bracket check:</strong> If your bonus will push income above a bracket threshold, consider how much more income falls into the higher bracket. Only the income above the threshold is taxed at the higher rate, so the impact may be smaller than you expect. Use our income tax calculator to see the exact effect on your return.</p></div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Is a bonus taxed differently than regular income?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">No. Bonuses are taxed as ordinary income at your marginal federal tax rate, exactly the same as regular wages. The difference you notice is in withholding — employers withhold a flat 22% from most bonuses under $1 million, which may be more or less than your actual marginal rate. You reconcile the difference on your tax return.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Does receiving a bonus push me into a higher tax bracket?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Only the portion of your bonus that exceeds the current bracket threshold is taxed at the higher rate. If you are in the 22% bracket and a bonus pushes $2,000 of income into the 24% bracket, only that $2,000 is taxed at 24%. The rest is still taxed at 22% and below. You are never worse off financially from receiving a bonus.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What FICA taxes apply to bonuses?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Bonuses are subject to Social Security tax (6.2% up to the $176,100 wage base in 2025) and Medicare tax (1.45% with no income cap). High earners also owe an additional 0.9% Additional Medicare Tax on wages above $200,000 for single filers. These FICA taxes apply regardless of your income tax bracket.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What if my employer pays my bonus taxes for me (gross-up)?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Some employers gross up bonus payments, meaning they pay an additional amount designed to cover the tax withholding so the employee receives the full intended bonus amount net of taxes. The grossed-up amount itself is also taxable income, which requires a calculation that accounts for the tax on the tax payment. If your employer does this, you will receive a larger gross bonus on your W-2.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Should I ask for my bonus to be paid in a different year?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">If you expect to be in a lower tax bracket next year — for example, because you plan to retire, take unpaid leave, or have lower income for another reason — deferring a bonus to January of the following year can reduce the tax. This requires coordination with your employer and depends on your company's policy. Bonus timing is a legitimate tax planning consideration for high earners.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

